- Related to [[Balanced scorecard|Balanced scorecard]] as budgeting is one of the major tools to translate strategic goals into financial plans
- Once the strategy is determined the budget can assist in translating the strategy to the day to day operations, by determining the expected sales, expected productions, required materials, labour and other resources. Besides planning, the budget is also a helpful tool for coordination of the business activities, motivation of people and control of the operational activities.
- Overall budget is built upon several individual budgets:
	- Sales or revenues budget
	- Trade receivable budget
	- Trade payable budget
	- Manufacturing budget
	- Production budget (labour, direct materials, overheads)
	- Raw material budget
	- Finished goods budget
	- Cash budget
- Budget process is often annual, starting with objective setting, followed by forecasting and creating plans and then regularly comparing the results with the plans and evaluating performance. This way management can keep control of the company's performance. 
Main Vocabulary:
- Cash budget: The cash budget contains the projected sources and uses of cash in a future period. This budget is used to establish whether a companyâ€™s operations will provide a sufficient amount of cash to meet the projected cash needed for example to buy raw materials and other resources 
- Revenue or Sales budget: A sales budget estimates the sales in units as well as the estimated earnings from these sales for a certain period 
- Production budget: A production budget determines the number of units to be produced to meet the sales targets and ending inventory needs for a certain period 
- Material budget: A materials budget determines the amount of materials are needed to meet the production requirements during a certain period Labour budget: 
- A labour budget forecasts the amount of labour hours needed to meet production requirements during a certain period

## Considerations
- Sales budget implies a certain amount of cash coming into the company so feeds into the trade receivables budget 
- These are all predictions so we need contingency built in (e.g. finished inventories budget has allowed here for 105 in case you sell more or there are defects - this goes beyond accounting)
- We also have overheads, Capex and direct labour which need to be estimated
- Cash budget shows feasibility of plan - if balance is negative or below amount allowed for borrowing etc, it means it cannoy go ahead and something needs to be changed. As such budgeting process is iterative - it is a feasibility test for the whole strategy of the organisation - that is why it is strategic budgeting.  
- A typical situation to be aware of is where, despite being very profitable, the business can be illiquid until it stops expanding. At that point, the growth of the cash inflows will catch up with that of the cash outflows and the net cash flow will be positiveâ€¦ and indeed very high if the firm has expanded for a long period of time! This is known as the **liquidity trap** or the **expansion trap**. Simplest solution is to slow expansion... or raise capital to cover shortfall - i.e. make a revision to the strategy

Links between [[Balanced scorecard|Balanced scorecard]] and Strategic budgeting
- BSC is a communication tool to make sure everyone in the organisation understands what the strategy is and how his or her actions contribute to realising the strategy
- Budgets represent all costs and predicted revenues which are caused by actions of people within the organisation. All of these decisions should be taken by thinking of which indicators of the BSC will be affected. 
- Strategically prepared budget should reflect line by line how to improve chances to reach each of the indicators of the BSC
- An example of a feasibility failure is the liquidity trap
